410→                           First asked and investigated by Riddell <a href="#cite-Ri69-201" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Ri69','201'); return false;">[Ri69]</a>. It is trivial that $G_k(N)\leq R_k(N)$, and it is possible that $G_k(N) &lt;R_k(N)$ (for example $G_3(5)=3$ and $R_3(5)=4$, and $G_3(14)\leq 7$ and $R_3(14)=8$).<br><br>Komlós, Sulyok, and Szemerédi <a href="#cite-KSS75-201" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('KSS75','201'); return false;">[KSS75]</a> have shown that $R_k(N) \ll_k G_k(N)$.
